# Session Start

## 1. Orient — run status

At the start of every session, run:

- **Orchestrator (main session):** `pnpm tg status --tasks` — full task list (Id, Title, Plan, Status, Owner). Use this so you see all active tasks, not just the 3 next runnable shown by default status.
- **Sub-agents (implementer, reviewer, etc.):** `pnpm tg status --tasks` — task list only; you don't need projects or initiatives. (Default status and `tg status --initiatives` show initiative rollup when the initiative table exists.)

```bash
# Orchestrator:
pnpm tg status --tasks

# Sub-agent (when you are executing a single task):
pnpm tg status --tasks
```

If `tg` fails (connection refused / timeout / read-only): do not retry; see **tg-usage.mdc § When Dolt is unavailable**.

Full task list surfaces:

- All active tasks (todo, doing, blocked) with plan and owner
- **Doing tasks** show owner — use for multi-agent (avoid overlapping files with another agent's task)
- Stale `doing` or forgotten `todo` tasks to clean up (see Recovery)

**Key constraints (see AGENT.md for details):**

- Sub-agent dispatch is **mandatory** for task execution — do not do the work yourself.
- Planner-analyst dispatch is **mandatory** before writing any plan.
- Feed up to 8 runnable non-conflicting tasks per batch; **max 8 sub-agents** at a time.
- Plans must have parallel-ready tasks (≥2 with no blockedBy).

**When multiple agents are active:** Read the "Active work" section. Avoid picking tasks that touch the same area/files as another agent's doing task. If overlap is detected, leave a `tg note` and pick a different task.

Address any stale `doing` tasks before starting new work. See **taskgraph-workflow.mdc → Recovery** for cleanup steps.

## 2. Model guidance — remind the user

After running status, include a brief model guidance note in your response.

**How the Task tool works:** there are only two model states — `model="fast"` (explicit fast model) or omit `model` (inherits from this session). Named model strings don't exist as Task tool values. Inherit-tier sub-agents (planner-analyst, reviewers, fixer, investigator) run on whatever model this orchestrator session is using — which is why the session model matters.

| Situation                                                   | Recommended           | Notes                                                                               |
| ----------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **This session** (orchestrator)                             | **Sonnet**            | Inherit-tier sub-agents (analysts, reviewers, fixer) automatically use this         |
| **`/work`** (autonomous execution)                          | **Auto**              | Fine — implementers get `fast`, inherit-tier agents get the session model           |
| **Escalating yourself directly** (after sub-agent failures) | **Opus if available** | Switch your session when doing hard direct execution that sub-agents couldn't solve |

**How to communicate this:** At session start, after the status output, add one line:

> Model check: Sonnet recommended for this session — analysts and reviewers inherit it automatically. Switch to Opus only if escalating a hard task yourself.

If the user mentions they're on a different model, flag it:

> Inherit-tier sub-agents (planner-analyst, reviewers, fixer) run on the session model. Sonnet gives the best balance for orchestrator sessions.
